Here is the complete plan — only **`common/chat.cpp`** is touched (two insertions of purely new code; no existing function or header is changed):

---

### What the template source looks like (reference: `mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja`)
The Mistral Nemo Jinja template contains `[INST]` and `[/INST]` but **no** `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`. That is the distinguishing fingerprint.

---

### Step 1 — New handler function (~line 1517, after `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3`, before `namespace workaround`)

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template & tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;
    data.preserved_tokens  = { "[INST]", "[/INST]" };

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();
    return data;
}
```

- `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl()` renders the Jinja template — system prepending and `[INST]/[/INST]` wrapping are already encoded in the model's own Jinja template; no manual message-munging needed.
- `[INST]`/`[/INST]` are preserved tokens so the grammar generator never fragments them.
- Minimal PEG parser: match the generation-prompt prefix, capture everything else as content. `</s>` is the model's EOS and is handled by the inference engine, so no extra stop tokens are required.

---

### Step 2 — Detection block (~line 1690, just before `return std::nullopt;` in `common_chat_try_specialized_template`)

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v3 — [INST]/[/INST] without [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
    // [SYSTEM_PROMPT] absence distinguishes this from Ministral 3 (and Mistral v7).
    if (src.find("[INST]")          != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[/INST]")         != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Ordering is safe:** the Ministral 3 check (which requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`) runs first, so it can never fall through to this new check. All other existing checks use entirely unrelated sentinel tokens.
